[[Category:Honiara| ]] [[Category:Oceanian culture]] [[Category:Polynesian culture]]

{{italic title}} '''''La Jeune Belgique''''' (meaning ''The Young Belgium'' in English) was a [[Belgian literature |Belgian literary]] society and movement that published a French-language literary review ''La Jeune Belgique'' between 1880 and 1897.<ref name=rut>{{cite web|title=Guide to the European Nineteenth-Century Rare Journals at the Zimmerli Art Museum at Rutgers University|url=http://www.zimmerlimuseum.rutgers.edu/finding-aid-nineteenth-c-journals|work=Rutgers University|accessdate=31 May 2015|date=March 2013}}</ref> Both the society and magazine were founded by the Belgian poet [[Max Waller (writer)|Max Waller]].<ref name=rut/> Contributors to the review included [[Georges Rodenbach]], [[Eugene Demolder]], [[Émile Verhaeren]], [[Maurice Maeterlinck]], [[Albert Giraud]], [[Georges Eekhoud]], [[Camille Lemonnier]] and [[Auguste Jennart]].
The magazine was started in 1880 under the name ''La Jeune revue littéraire'' which was changed to ''La Jeune Belgique'' in 1881.<ref name=rut/> The headquarters of the magazine, which was published biweekly, was in [[Brussels]].<ref name=rut/> In its later year the frequency of the magazine became published monthly and then, bimonthly.<ref name=rut/> In addition, the magazine was published both in Brussels and in [[Paris]] during this period.<ref name=rut/>
==References== {{Reflist}} *{{cite book|author=Charles Dudley Warner|year=1897|page=5189|title=Library of the World's Best Literature, Ancient and Modern, volume XIII|publisher=The International Society|location=New York }}
