{{Infobox person | name =Ludmila K. Foxlee | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Ludmila Kuchar | birth_date = {{Birth date|1885|08|13}} | birth_place =[[Czech Republic]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1971|04|15|1885|08|13|mf=y}} | death_place =[[New York, New York]] | death_cause = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | occupation = [[Social Worker]], [[Teacher]], [[Interpreter]] | spouse = John Foxlee | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = }}
'''Ludmila Kuchar Foxlee''' was a social worker at the [[Ellis Island]] immigration station. Employed by the [[YWCA]] after [[World War I]], Foxlee spent time in [[Czechoslovakia]] to assist in rebuilding efforts before working at Ellis Island from 1920 to 1937. She became one of most well-known immigrant aid workers<ref name="nps">{{cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/elis/learn/historyculture/people_immigrant_aid_worker.htm|publisher=nps.gov|title=Immigrant Aid Worker - Ellis Island Part of Statue of Liberty National Monument (U.S. National Park Service)|accessdate=2017-07-07}}</ref> and her meticulous notes are currently stored at the Ellis Island archives.
== Early life == Foxlee was born in [[Bohemia]] in 1885. She emigrated to the [[United States]] with her family in 1890.
== Social work == Foxlee helped thousands of detained immigrants at Ellis Island. She served as a translator, as she was fluent in several languages in addition to her native Czech. Foxlee was interested in the folk dress and music of newcomers. She also assisted in the immigrants' [[cultural assimilation]] to U.S. society, at times giving women a "makeover" with Americanized clothing.<ref name="independent">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/comment/a-cautionary-valentine-they-came-to-america-for-love-but-found-themselves-on-heartbreak-island-8495628.html|publisher=independent.co.uk|title=A cautionary Valentine: They came to America for love, but found themselves on Heartbreak Island &#124; The Independent|accessdate=2017-07-07}}</ref>
