{{more citations needed|date=February 2007}}
'''Wordsworth McAndrew''' (1936 – 25 April 2008)<ref>Gary Girdhari, [http://www.guyanajournal.com/Wordsworth_McAndrew.html "The Passing of a Great Artist: Wordsworth McAndrew"], ''Guyana Journal'', May 2008.</ref> was a leading [[Guyana]] [[folklore|folklorist]], poet, and creative artist.
==Biography== McAndrew was born in 1936 in [[Georgetown, Guyana|Georgetown]], [[British Guiana]], to Winslow Alexander McAndrew and Ivy McAndrew. His father was a schoolteacher, musician and catechist, who taught in rural Anglican schools. McAndrew was raised in Cummingsburg and, from the age of 12, in Newtown, Kitty. He attended "Teacher" Marshall Kindergarten School, Christ Church Primary School and [[Queen's College, Guyana|Queen's College]].<ref>[http://www.ecaroh.com/bmp/articles/wordsworth_mcandrew.htm "Wordsworth McAndrew - A Guyanese National Treasure"], eCaroh Caribbean Emporium.</ref>
Through his work as a radio broadcaster during the 1960s and 1970s, he helped the Guyanese recognize and feel proud of their mythological and folkloric heritage. He studied and celebrated Guyanese language and culture, using all media available to explain and promote Guyanese cultural characteristics.
McAndrew died on 25 April 2008, at the East Orange Hospital,<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2492&dat=20080426&id=UEZaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=oSYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=1767,8422776 "Wordsworth Mcandrew Dies At 72"], ''[[Stabroek News]]'', 26 April 2008, p. 16.</ref> in [[New Jersey]], where he had been living in self-imposed exile.<ref>[http://www.litguyana.000space.com/index.php/poems/36-wordsworth-mcandrew "Wordsworth McAndrew"], Literature Guyana.</ref>
==Legacy== The [[Wordsworth McAndrew Award]], founded in 2002 to celebrate Guyanese who have made important contributions to the country's cultural life, was named in his honour.
==References== {{Reflist}}
